Firefighters and police were seen outside the office of Mike Freer MP

Police are investigating a suspected arson attack at the office of North London Conservative MP Mike Freer.

A fire broke out at the rear of the North Finchley and Golders Green MP's constituency office at around 19:00 on Christmas Eve.

The Met Police confirmed it is investigating the fire.

Mr Freer told the BBC the fire happened at the rear of the premises and no one was in the building at the time of the incident.

He continued: "The police and fire brigade were on the scene in minutes and have been incredible in their response."

London Fire Brigade (LFB) confirmed the fire started in a shed outside the office before spreading to the rest of the building.

An LFB spokesperson said: "An external shed was destroyed by fire. Part of the first, second and third floors of the property were also damaged by the blaze."

In a statement, a Metropolitan Police spokesperson said: "The cause of the fire is under investigation as it is believed it may have been started deliberately. There have been no arrests."

Pictures posted on social media showed Metropolitan Police and LFB vehicles at the premises on Sunday evening.

Mr Freer has represented the North London constituency since 2010.

He is parliamentary under-secretary of state for courts and legal services, a junior role in the Ministry of Justice.

Pictures show the fire spread to an office inside the building

Detectives and ambulance workers were seen outside the apartment complex of pop star Rihanna 

Police are investigating a suspicious disturbance at the apartment building of West End performer Rihanna.

A ruckus broke out at the rear of Rihanna's Beverly Hills penthouse apartment at around 3:30 am.

The LAPD confirmed it is looking into the incident.

Rihanna told a journalist on the condition of anonymity that the ruckus happened at the rooftop area of the premises and no one was harmed in the incident.

She continued: "The security personnel and fire department were on the scene in minutes and have been professional in their response."

LA Fire Department (LAFD) confirmed the noise started at the pool area of the complex before spreading to other areas of the building.

A LAFD spokesperson said: "A poolside disturbance resulted in no one being transported to the hospital. Fire damaged some outdoor decorations."

In a statement, a Los Angeles Police Department spokesperson said: "The cause of the ruckus is under investigation as it is believed it may have been a party gone wrong. No arrests have been made."

Pictures posted on social media showed LAPD and LAFD vehicles at the premise in the early hours of the morning.

Rihanna has lived in the West End neighborhood since moving there in 2010.

Rihanna is a global pop sensation known for her chart-topping hits and sold-out world tours.

Detectives and paramedics were seen outside the beachfront villa of reggae star Shaggy, a longtime resident of the exclusive Jamaican coastal community.

The Jamaica Police Force is probing an unexpected gathering at Shaggy's private compound in Half Moon Bay, which erupted into a lively celebration around 10 pm.

Waves crashed into the shore as the impromptu bash spilled onto the beach outside Shaggy's sprawling residence, catching authorities off guard.

"I heard the music and revelry getting louder by the minute," said a neighboring resident, who wished to remain anonymous. "Then, sirens began blaring and police lights flickering everywhere."

Shaggy, in a statement to a local journalist, disclosed that the ruckus started at the backyard bar of his beachside paradise, spreading to other areas of the villa as the evening wore on. "The island rhythms just took over, and the next thing we knew, people were having the time of their lives."

Confirming the incident, Chief Inspector Winston Davis told us: "As far as we can gather, it appears to have been an un authorized but well-controlled gathering that got a bit out of hand." Miraculously, no one was injured, and damage was minimal, although some decorative palm trees got damaged.

Pictures posted on social media depicted law enforcement and medical personnel scoping out the situation under stars just above Shaggy's shimmering swimming pool.

Shaggy's West Kingston neighborhood will remain quiet once the sun rises over the turquoise waters, grateful that all that dancing and song did not escalate into something far more serious. This, however, marked the second high-profile party to spill onto the exclusive shoreline within weeks, the previous incident involving renowned DJ Mavado.

Celebrity DJ Questlove found himself in an unexpected impromptu jam session outside his luxurious estate in Princeton, New Jersey, early Sunday morning. Guests and onlookers alike swayed to the pulsating rhythms as the party spilled onto the snow-melted lawn. Neighbors, mostly sleepy-eyed parents with sleepy-eyed kids, shook their heads good-naturedly, too enchanted by the infectious beats to protest.

"It was like nothing I've ever experienced," described Lisa Brown, who lives next door. "One moment, I'm reading a bedtime story to the kids, the next, the air is filled with funk, drums, and whoops. When the police arrived, I just went, 'Oh, it's Questlove having a party again!'."
